State of São Paulo registers 90% increase in cases of hepatitis A in 2025
-------------------------------------------------------------------------

The state of São Paulo registered 949 cases of hepatitis A in the first half of 2025, against 498 in the same period of 2024. Data from the State Health Department (SES) reveal an increase of 90.5%. The capital of São Paulo alone concentrated 476 cases of the disease between January 1 and July 2, 2025, according to the Municipal Health Department.

Vaccination is the main form of prevention against the disease. Available for free through the Unified Health System, one-dose immunization is recommended for children at 15 months, but can be applied up to 5 years of age. The 2-dose schedule is recommended for people with liver diseases, chronic carriers of hepatitis B, people with HIV or using HIV pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), immunosuppressive diseases, and in addition to transplant patients.

In the capital, 4543 doses of the vaccine in adults were applied from January to June 2024. The number increased to 9487 in the same period in 2025 -- an increase of 108.8%. However, vaccination in children suffered a drop of 9.7% in the city of São Paulo. In the first half of 2025, 55 160 doses were administered, compared to 61 085 last year [2024].

In a note, the SES informed that "it continuously follows and monitors the cases of hepatitis A registered in the state. The Ministry, in partnership with the 645 municipalities of São Paulo, has been carrying out training actions for health professionals and testing for the population to detect the disease."

According to the city hall, the main measures to prevent hepatitis A are:
- Wash hands (after using the toilet, changing diapers and before preparing food);
- Wash food consumed raw with treated, chlorinated or boiled water, leaving it to soak for 30 minutes;
- Cook food well before consumption, especially shellfish, seafood and fish;
- Properly sanitize plates, glasses, cutlery and bottles;
- Use adequate sanitary facilities;
- In places such as daycare centers, schools, cafeterias, restaurants and closed institutions, adopt strict hygiene measures, such as disinfecting surfaces with 2.5% sodium hypochlorite or bleach;
- Avoid bathing and playing in ditches, streams, fountains, flood areas or near sewage;
- Avoid the construction of cesspools near wells and springs;
- Use condoms and perform hygiene of the genital, perineum and anal regions before and after sexual intercourse.

[Byline: Felipe Cruz]

